<div id="review_1082451804" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1082451804" />
    <a title="Inês Montenegro" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4802863-in-s-montenegro"><img alt="Inês Montenegro" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400350730p2/4802863.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1082451804?book_show_action=true">Oct 17, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inês Montenegro" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inês Montenegro" href="/user/show/4802863-in-s-montenegro">Inês Montenegro</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1082451804" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15351126246088506338">It’s not usual to see such a great characterization of 13-yearl-old kids. In my experience, authors either try to make them “mature” by using vocabulary and behaviors which sound way too unnatural for them, or just infantile them too much, while trying to mimic a language which, once again, makes them seem unnatural, while annoying the reader. Sanchez didn’t fall in any of these. The story is narrated through the viewpoint of two different kids beginning to understand themselves and, basically, </span>
  <span id="freeText15351126246088506338" style="display:none">It’s not usual to see such a great characterization of 13-yearl-old kids. In my experience, authors either try to make them “mature” by using vocabulary and behaviors which sound way too unnatural for them, or just infantile them too much, while trying to mimic a language which, once again, makes them seem unnatural, while annoying the reader. Sanchez didn’t fall in any of these. The story is narrated through the viewpoint of two different kids beginning to understand themselves and, basically, grow up in all the complicated stuff. While keeping distinct voices, both Xio and Frederick sounded perfectly as their age – damn, it reminded me how I was at thirteen, and for the first time, it made me do it without do it without the extra “I should be more this or less that… I wish I could turn back in time”. After all, we all need time to figure things out, especially when they bring a huge change in our lives – and that’s what this book is about.<br />The public which this book is targeted is a younger one – kids around the age of the protagonists, kids who are at the beginning – or middle – of their adolescence. And I’m happy for that: this book may help a lot of them, either with their sexuality, or concerning any other “Is this who I am? But they will crucify me at school!” issues. We need more of these books. However, I do not think it stops in there. I’m in my mid-twenties, and I could not have enjoyed this more. The writing is simple and easy, but not at all simplistic. The story is sweet. The characters are well build and believable. The theme is fantastic: something we always need to be reminded of. And I won’t lie and say that maybe, just maybe, I did need for someone to remind me what being thirteen years old felt like. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15351126246088506338" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


